Winner is @thefairbanksfam 

🎉GIVEAWAY🎉 
There’s nothing more priceless than your photo and video memories.  That’s why I am so excited to team up with @urlifemedia to offer an amazing GIVEAWAY!!!!

I take a ton of photos and videos, and I am sure you do, too. I always procrastinate pulling them together into videos because the process is time consuming and overwhelming.  That’s where my new favorite indulgence @URLIFEMEDIA comes in.  They have Hollywood producers on staff to turn your footage into amazing memories.  You don’t have to worry about wasting time going through your videos and choosing the best footage, they do it for you 😳 with prices starting as low as $75. 

When I got our completed Christmas video back, I heard things I didn’t even realize had happened (listen closely for Savannah saying “that’s weird” when Santa drives a car). The film captures our family and holiday celebration perfectly and it will help the kids remember our quarantine Christmas for many years to come.  After you’ve seen, it I wonder who will want to have Christmas at our house next year 😂? 

We want to share this experience with someone else by giving away one custom 2.5 minute Hollywood level URLIFE movie (value $595). 

To enter 
1.Follow @bennetttriplets and @urlifemedia on IG.
2.Comment below and tell me what your first URLIFE project will be about (my next project is going to be a fun day trip we took to the Safari Park) it could be anything - a previous vacation, year in review, birthday. . . really anything.
3. Don’t let your friends miss out.  Tag a couple of busy moms who would love to win. If you share this post in your story and tag us, you’ll get another entry. 

We’ll go live next Saturday 2/8 and the triplets will draw a winner.  We will continue working with @urlifemedia, so I will have discount codes coming up and so much more!

node.text:
We wrapped up the first week of in person school with all 3 getting sick.  I expected it, as they haven’t been around too many other children to have a strong immunity built up.

Beau had a slight fever last night and all 3 are now coughing and congested.  I kept them home from school today, but the school nurse called and said that due to their symptoms they can’t come back until they have a negative COVID test and no cough.  It’s clearly going to be a few days until they can return to school no matter what the test results show. 

Here’s to a speedy recovery and a negative test result. 🤞🏻.

I might look like I am surrounded by a trio of cuties but they sure can get up to some shenanigans.  My feed is for all the cute pics, but my story will show you the REAL us. If you haven’t stopped by in a while – you should go take a peek.  In the past 24 hours I’ve posted about Savannah’s wannabe boyfriend and Beau’s wardrobe malfunction. 

As an update on Savannah’s current relationship status – I have come to learn that Vincent is a bit of a player.  The day before he told Savannah he had a crush on her he apparently had a crush on another girl.  First grade love is rather fleeting 😂. 

Side note - I have heard from a couple of you that our posts aren’t showing up in your feed.  Make sure to like/comment or go click on our story so you continue to see all the triplet cuteness.  If you don’t show the love, Instagram thinks you no longer want to see our posts.

node.text:
Bring a mom has never been easy, but being a mom during a pandemic is especially challenging.  We’re trying to do the best we can, to make decisions about our children’s health and safety when the world is completely divided and none of us can predict the future. 

Last year I kept the kids as virtual learners, as it was an option that the school district made available to us.  This year it’s not an option and here in Texas masks are optional, so parents have a lot of last minute deciding to do as transmission rates are spiking .  I am second guessing myself and the decisions that we had previously made regarding the children’s education and attending in person school. 

Yesterday I sat @jason.a.bennett down and told him all of my concerns. We talked it through and we made a big last minute change to our plans.  I emailed my requests to the Vice principal (who even responded on a Sunday). He understands my concerns and is willing to make some adjustments to accommodate us.

We are requesting the kids to all be in the same class to minimize exposure. 

I spoke about it on my story this morning. 

How are you feeling about sending your children back to school in person?  Are you comfortable with it and how your school district is handling everything? Moms of multiples, have you made any decisions about classes based on the ever changing pandemic?? 👇

node.text:
Today is the last day of breast-feeding week. I usually don’t talk about it because breastfeeding is a very personal struggle for many women and my nature is to be inclusive and not alienate anyone. Since it’s such a sensitive topic, it’s usually off limits for me on this public forum.

But here’s my story:

I didn’t start off my journey with any real expectations. I knew I was willing to give it a try, but I figured feeding 3 would likely be impossible, so I didn’t want to put that kind of pressure on myself.

From the moment they were born I was pumping. It gradually became a game… a challenge really… to keep up with the demands of feeding 3 and I am so honored to say that they didn’t have a single formula bottle ever! I pumped for 45 minutes every 3 hours. That means that from the time I started to get set up to the minute I put the milk in the refrigerator and washed everything it would have taken over an hour. Then I had less than 2 hours before I had to do it all over again. I pumped all day and all night that first year. In that year of pumping I missed only 1 single session. I learned to pump while sitting up and dozing. I pumped in the car and I pumped from the office. I pumped over a half a gallon a day as I neared the end of my pumping and breastfeeding journey. I had a freezer stocked with milk and gradually slowed around 11 months, making sure there was enough to see them through until their first birthday. If you swipe you’ll see the different colored stickers indicating the month and the crock pot we used to warm the milk for each feeding session.

I don’t miss pumping, but I am so grateful my body was able to grow and nourish those 3 tiny humans in utero and a year following. I know we all have different journeys and I gave up a lot to meet that goal. Looking back I am not sure how I did it, but I am so grateful that I did.

Here’s to all you pumping mamas. We sometimes don’t get the credit because we chose a slightly different path. I am here to support and encourage and I would be honored to help if you are struggling, just send me a DM. #breastfeeding #worldbreastfeedingweek #breastfeedingmultiples #breastfeedingtriplets #exclusivepumping

node.text:
The triplets are starting back to school next week and summer is coming to a close for them.  Even things at work are having a temporary lull.  I shuffled the kids out the door today to go to the park with our nanny, and actually had some time to pick up around the house.  I tidied up some in the pantry, cleaned the fish tanks, put up my laundry and under most circumstances I would feel so accomplished.  But instead of patting myself on the back, as I sat down on the sofa I actually felt incredibly sad. 

For years I have waited for the kids to go to school.  All I wanted was a few minutes to myself – some peacefulness. I wanted to calm the chaos. 

Now I am sitting here in the peace and quiet trying to find a little clarity – I am thinking about empty nesters and the stay-at-home moms who are about to send their kids off to school.  I’ll still have work to occupy my mind, but in this moment I realize that we are about to start a completely different chapter of our lives.  I am sure it will be amazing, but today it’s feeling pretty darn tough.
